%BOM---------------------
Date:9/4/2010 12:49:57 AM
From:Paul Senior
EKS. We amateurs really only do part of what the pro analysts do when they
evaluate these companies.

Which is, I believe:

They try to id a shale play or company early on.

They use their knowledge of geology and technical aspects of extracting oil
from those formations in order to assess the technical risk.

They use their knowledge of petroleum accounting to study the the financial
statements of the company--- well-by-well if such info. is available.

Doesn't mean amateur analysts can't do okay though.
=============================
I'm not detailed enough or astute enough though to seek out and catch the
hidden assets that you find that others overlook. I am trying to find the next
good oil shale plays that might make the fortunes of small e&p companies
though. The Bakken, which I like and am in with several stocks, seems fairly
well known now. I use Big Dog's Boom Boom thread as an indicator: If there's
lots of discussion on a subject there, it's my signal that being an early
entrant to the stock or shale isn't likely for me. One shale area that hasn't
garnered much if any interest around here that I like and posted on is Eagle
Ford for horizontal drilling possibilities. So I'm one who's buying stock in
some companies interested in developing their land holdings there.
