From:Paul Senior
GTSI. A stock well known to some of us.

I don't know exactly what it's business is now. It sold upgraded computers and
computer software primarily or solely to the US Govt, and that abruptly ended
when the contracts weren't renewed.

I'd be interested in the company again when it's a net net.

Right now company is overvalued -- my opinion of course. It's return on equity
is terrible, regardless of its stated book value. Profit margins aren't good at
all. OTOH, p/sales is low, so maybe they can eke some higher profits on future
sales.

(I'm just looking at the overall company, from a Yahoo/SI stat page.)

The company's hidden asset has earnings that can be taken into GTSI's balance
sheet. It's an asset though that GTSI maybe can control or maybe not. They may
or may not easily dispose of their portion of that business or force a sale of
the company or manage the direction of that company. So it's a second business
that the small stockholder has to be concerned about. If the analyst values
those earnings at 7.5x, then maybe GTSI should be valued only at 7.5x too. (I
don't know.) Currently the p/e is 13 with forward p/e 8.5x.

I've had mixed success trading stocks where the hidden assets are shares of
other companies. The gist is that the sum of the shares of all the businesses
(often easily calculated because the companies are publicly traded), that the
mother company has is higher than the enterprise value of the mother company
itself. Thus a margin of safety, and an opportunity for the mother stock to
rise if/as one or more of the holding company stocks do well. The issue is that
everything sometimes seems to be correlated, and/or the value does not seem to
close,or I've had to wait a very long time to see success - the dinkier the
company, the longer the wait (it seems).

If you buy, Rainmaker888, you may find your experience different from mine. For
me, the stock's just worth a bet to me at current price. GL.
